1
00:00:23,106 --> 00:00:26,644
Stroke! Stroke!

2
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:31,733
Stroke! Stroke!

3
00:00:32,950 --> 00:00:36,192
Stroke! Stroke!

4
00:00:55,472 --> 00:00:56,712
Come on, come on.

5
00:01:01,144 --> 00:01:03,305
Pick him up, pick him up.

6
00:01:03,397 --> 00:01:05,012
Son of a bitch!

7
00:01:05,107 --> 00:01:07,473
I mean, Your Honor, that was a hell of a shot.

8
00:01:09,403 --> 00:01:12,270
Well, I'm currently doing an
externship for two extra credits

9
00:01:12,364 --> 00:01:14,446
as a clerk for Judge Hookstratten.

10
00:01:14,533 --> 00:01:16,865
BJ Hookstratten?

11
00:01:16,952 --> 00:01:20,570
That's more impressive than being in the top 5%.

12
00:01:20,664 --> 00:01:23,280
Look, I don't know what kind of
offers you've had from Wall Street...

13
00:01:23,375 --> 00:01:26,287
The top five, sir. In my class.

14
00:01:26,378 --> 00:01:27,993
Not the top 5%. I'm sorry, I just...

15
00:01:28,088 --> 00:01:31,296
Mr. McDeere, we've just offered you $68,000 a year

16
00:01:31,383 --> 00:01:33,749
from arguably the leading law firm in Chicago.

17
00:01:33,844 --> 00:01:35,630
Is there somewhere else you have to be?

18
00:01:35,721 --> 00:01:37,461
Yes, sir. I have a job. I'm just on lunch break.

19
00:01:38,557 --> 00:01:40,343
I know you've had a lot of offers.

20
00:01:40,434 --> 00:01:43,392
Did you know, for example, that we have 127 clients

21
00:01:43,478 --> 00:01:46,345
that are Fortune 500 companies?
Now, look, we'll offer you $74,000...

22
00:01:46,440 --> 00:01:49,273
our billing requirement for a
first-year associate is only 2,000 hours,

23
00:01:49,359 --> 00:01:52,522
not the usual 25 or 26 or 2,700.

24
00:01:52,613 --> 00:01:55,446
We want you to have a life outside the office, Mitch.

25
00:01:55,532 --> 00:01:58,274
And if you're a Lakers fan, we
have a fabulous box at the Forum.

26
00:02:04,791 --> 00:02:06,873
I know there are firms from all over the country

27
00:02:06,960 --> 00:02:09,417
that have been up here offering you everything.

28
00:02:09,504 --> 00:02:12,621
But with your ability and ambition,
there is only one place for you,

29
00:02:12,716 --> 00:02:13,831
and that's with our firm in Washington...

30
00:02:13,925 --> 00:02:15,381
Let's stop talking about the ribbon on the package,

31
00:02:15,469 --> 00:02:17,505
and start talking about what's in the package.

32
00:02:17,596 --> 00:02:20,053
One of our partners is an
ex-governor, two are congressmen

33
00:02:20,140 --> 00:02:22,131
and one's a former Senator of Agriculture.

34
00:02:23,727 --> 00:02:25,843
May I take your coat, sir?

35
00:02:40,577 --> 00:02:41,737
- Mitchell McDeere, right?
- Yes.

36
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:43,910
Lamar Quinn. Come on in.

37
00:02:44,831 --> 00:02:46,367
I'd like you to meet

38
00:02:46,458 --> 00:02:49,825
- Oliver Lambert, our senior partner.
- Mitch. Mitch.

39
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:51,581
- How do you do, sir?
- This is Royce McKnight,

40
00:02:51,672 --> 00:02:52,787
- our managing partner.
- How do you do, sir?

41
00:02:52,881 --> 00:02:54,792
- Welcome.
- Care for a drink?

42
00:02:54,883 --> 00:02:57,499
- No, I'm fine.
- Take a seat, Mitch.

43
00:03:01,014 --> 00:03:02,470
Tired of interviews?

44
00:03:02,557 --> 00:03:05,264
No, sir. I just don't quite know what to say.

45
00:03:05,352 --> 00:03:07,183
Unusual for a lawyer.

46
00:03:07,270 --> 00:03:10,387
I can get tongue-tied in any
number of situations, sir,

47
00:03:10,482 --> 00:03:12,894
but it's usually with my wife.

48
00:03:12,984 --> 00:03:16,476
Would you mind describing one, with your wife?

49
00:03:18,573 --> 00:03:21,064
The first time I saw her.

50
00:03:21,159 --> 00:03:22,945
Any time we argue.

51
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:27,621
Whenever she walks into a room, as a matter of fact.

52
00:03:27,708 --> 00:03:30,950
Might we ask about the rest of your family?

53
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:34,377
My father was killed in the coal mines

54
00:03:34,464 --> 00:03:37,171
and my mother remarried and lives in Florida.

55
00:03:37,259 --> 00:03:39,215
Brothers and sisters?

56
00:03:40,345 --> 00:03:41,551
None.

57
00:03:41,638 --> 00:03:45,426
Mitch, I hope you don't think us intrusive,

58
00:03:45,517 --> 00:03:49,726
but stability in the family
has a special importance for us.

59
00:03:49,813 --> 00:03:53,601
Bendini, Lambert & Locke is just a small Memphis firm,

60
00:03:53,692 --> 00:03:55,603
41 lawyers.

61
00:03:55,694 --> 00:03:59,812
But we're a large family. So we're careful.

62
00:03:59,906 --> 00:04:03,319
Now, sir, do you have any questions for us?

63
00:04:04,661 --> 00:04:07,323
Do you have an offer in mind?

64
00:04:13,211 --> 00:04:16,248
It includes a bonus schedule,

65
00:04:16,339 --> 00:04:19,752
a low-interest mortgage so you can buy a home,

66
00:04:19,843 --> 00:04:24,212
country club membership, and
we'll lease you a new Mercedes.

67
00:04:24,306 --> 00:04:25,341
You pick the color, Mitch.

68
00:04:25,432 --> 00:04:27,263
Lamar, you haven't been paying attention.

69
00:04:27,350 --> 00:04:29,466
His wife picks the color.

70
00:04:35,066 --> 00:04:38,354
- Do I... Do I open it here?
- Of course.

71
00:04:38,445 --> 00:04:41,152
Unless you can tell us what's in it.

72
00:04:42,949 --> 00:04:46,942
A lawyer worth that offer
shouldn't have to open the envelope.

73
00:04:54,961 --> 00:04:57,543
Mr. McKnight, you are the managing partner

74
00:04:57,631 --> 00:04:59,667
at Bendini, Lambert & Locke, is that correct?

75
00:04:59,758 --> 00:05:00,793
Yes.

76
00:05:00,884 --> 00:05:02,169
Did Mr. Lambert, as senior partner,

77
00:05:02,260 --> 00:05:05,047
give you any instructions regarding my employment?

78
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:06,378
He did.

79
00:05:07,766 --> 00:05:11,429
And, Mr. McKnight, do you usually
follow Mr. Lambert's instructions?

80
00:05:11,520 --> 00:05:14,637
Objection. Vague. Ambiguous.

81
00:05:14,731 --> 00:05:16,096
Sustained.

82
00:05:19,069 --> 00:05:22,436
What precisely were those instructions?

83
00:05:22,531 --> 00:05:24,988
That you were in great demand,
and I should make certain

84
00:05:25,075 --> 00:05:29,444
that we obtained your services
before a bidding situation developed.

85
00:05:30,705 --> 00:05:33,321
How did you go about making certain?

86
00:05:34,501 --> 00:05:37,959
I bribed a clerk in the Harvard Law placement office

87
00:05:38,046 --> 00:05:40,958
for the exact amount of the highest offer,

88
00:05:42,259 --> 00:05:44,250
and then added 20%.

89
00:05:45,637 --> 00:05:48,925
Mitch, the letter you got from Bendini, Lambert & Locke

90
00:05:49,015 --> 00:05:52,178
was the only one sent out. We want you.

91
00:06:20,839 --> 00:06:22,079
Okay.

92
00:06:22,966 --> 00:06:25,753
You're gonna have to leave
now. I'm expecting my husband.

93
00:06:25,844 --> 00:06:27,584
The hell with him.

94
00:06:28,680 --> 00:06:30,136
Come here.

95
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:37,636
Moo shu pork, Szechwan beef,
mandarin duck from Wong Boys.

96
00:06:40,734 --> 00:06:42,099
It's even got a cork.

97
00:06:42,193 --> 00:06:43,854
What's going on?

98
00:06:44,487 --> 00:06:47,354
You remember the letter I
got from that firm in Memphis?

99
00:06:47,449 --> 00:06:48,814
Memphis?

100
00:06:48,909 --> 00:06:50,945
That's what I thought, until their offer.

101
00:06:51,036 --> 00:06:52,572
What was the offer?

102
00:06:52,662 --> 00:06:55,574
They didn't say. It's in there.

103
00:07:01,171 --> 00:07:02,786
It's sealed.

104
00:07:02,881 --> 00:07:04,212
I guessed.

105
00:07:04,841 --> 00:07:06,047
What?

106
00:07:06,134 --> 00:07:08,420
Yeah, but I'm a good guesser.

107
00:07:17,270 --> 00:07:19,932
Plus a 5% increase the second year.

108
00:07:20,690 --> 00:07:22,351
Why?

109
00:07:22,692 --> 00:07:25,809
"Why?" Whose side are you on anyway?

110
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:28,653
Yours.

111
00:07:28,740 --> 00:07:31,482
Plus bonuses, plus a low interest mortgage...

112
00:07:31,576 --> 00:07:33,191
As in a home, with grass around it?

113
00:07:33,286 --> 00:07:36,904
They want to fly us down to Memphis for a little visit.

114
00:08:04,067 --> 00:08:06,558
If you've been in one limo, you've been in them all.

115
00:08:14,911 --> 00:08:17,368
Bye. See you later, Your Honor.

116
00:08:25,797 --> 00:08:27,082
Sir.

117
00:08:31,553 --> 00:08:33,043
Hey, Mitch.

118
00:08:33,763 --> 00:08:34,798
Come on, associates first,

119
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:37,631
then lunch with the partners
in our private dining room.

120
00:08:38,852 --> 00:08:41,559
He's our number one draft pick, so to speak,

121
00:08:41,646 --> 00:08:45,559
and he's being romanced by the big boys

122
00:08:45,650 --> 00:08:47,766
from New York and Chicago and everywhere else,

123
00:08:47,902 --> 00:08:52,111
so we have to sell him on our
little firm here in Memphis.

124
00:08:52,240 --> 00:08:55,277
Meanwhile, he's gonna try not to be embarrassed

125
00:08:55,368 --> 00:08:59,452
while I remind you that he's about
to graduate from Harvard with honors.

126
00:08:59,581 --> 00:09:00,616
Hear, hear.

127
00:09:06,921 --> 00:09:08,457
No one's divorced in the Firm?

128
00:09:08,590 --> 00:09:10,455
No one's divorced in the Firm.

129
00:09:10,550 --> 00:09:13,132
- Impossible.
- No bachelors either.

130
00:09:13,803 --> 00:09:15,134
What about women?

131
00:09:15,221 --> 00:09:17,303
- They had one once.
- Only one?

132
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:20,553
Alice Krauss, wobbled around on 4" heels.

133
00:09:20,643 --> 00:09:22,975
Affirmative action on stilts.

134
00:09:23,104 --> 00:09:25,891
All white, all male, all married, huh?

135
00:09:32,739 --> 00:09:35,902
- What the hell is this?
- There he goes.

136
00:09:35,992 --> 00:09:37,152
Hey!

137
00:09:59,182 --> 00:10:01,013
It's different from the northeast.

138
00:10:01,101 --> 00:10:04,309
The pace, we're almost stately by comparison.

139
00:10:05,021 --> 00:10:08,434
Courteous and not as gossipy.

140
00:10:08,525 --> 00:10:10,686
We keep each other's secrets.

141
00:10:10,777 --> 00:10:12,187
I like that.

142
00:10:13,488 --> 00:10:15,604
What do you like about it?

143
00:10:16,699 --> 00:10:20,112
All of it. It's a family. Just the way you said.

144
00:10:29,045 --> 00:10:30,376
For the last three years,

145
00:10:30,505 --> 00:10:32,962
I've been teaching in the
Boston area at a private school.

146
00:10:33,049 --> 00:10:34,209
Do you work?

147
00:10:34,342 --> 00:10:36,799
Well, not since I put Lamar through law school.

148
00:10:36,886 --> 00:10:38,797
But, you know, working isn't forbidden.

149
00:10:38,888 --> 00:10:41,379
- Forbidden?
- Working, by the Firm, you know.

150
00:10:41,474 --> 00:10:43,635
- How could it be forbidden?
- It isn't.

151
00:10:43,726 --> 00:10:47,810
Anyway, two babies in 14 months and
I had all the work I could handle.

152
00:10:47,897 --> 00:10:50,559
- Do you plan to start a family?
- Maybe in a couple of years.

153
00:10:50,692 --> 00:10:52,557
The Firm encourages children.

154
00:10:52,694 --> 00:10:54,230
How do they do that exactly?

155
00:11:02,370 --> 00:11:04,577
Hey, how about it?

156
00:11:04,664 --> 00:11:06,245
How about it.

157
00:11:09,002 --> 00:11:13,336
Okay, okay. The Love Boat band, the secret recipe ribs,

158
00:11:13,423 --> 00:11:14,663
they're a little square maybe...

159
00:11:14,757 --> 00:11:18,090
I don't mind square. I like square. Weird, I mind.

160
00:11:18,720 --> 00:11:20,256
What do you mean, "weird"?

161
00:11:20,346 --> 00:11:21,586
Well, here's a quote.

162
00:11:21,681 --> 00:11:25,674
"The Firm does not forbid me to take
a job, and they encourage children."

163
00:11:25,768 --> 00:11:27,349
Ask me why.

164
00:11:27,437 --> 00:11:29,018
Because they love kids.

165
00:11:29,105 --> 00:11:31,687
Because children promote stability.

166
00:11:32,442 --> 00:11:34,182
Want to hear more?

167
00:11:36,112 --> 00:11:37,602
No, you're right.

168
00:11:38,239 --> 00:11:40,446
Don't pay any attention. I'm just
gonna throw myself over the rail.

169
00:11:40,575 --> 00:11:44,238
- I think my will is self-explanatory.
- Okay, okay, okay.

170
00:11:45,288 --> 00:11:46,949
These are nice people, Abby.

171
00:11:47,040 --> 00:11:48,530
These are nice people. Okay.

172
00:11:48,625 --> 00:11:50,866
I'm more impressed with it than
you are. You grew up with it.

173
00:11:50,960 --> 00:11:54,953
Do you know what $96,000 a year is here?

174
00:11:55,089 --> 00:11:56,795
It's like 150 in New York.

175
00:11:56,883 --> 00:11:58,794
Did you ever think I'd make a six-figure salary?

176
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:00,546
Absolutely.

177
00:12:01,471 --> 00:12:02,881
You did?

178
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:10,302
Well, your folks! Your folks
are only a few hours away, too.

179
00:12:10,438 --> 00:12:12,724
You mean, if we fight, I don't have far to drive.

180
00:12:12,815 --> 00:12:14,305
Exactly.

181
00:12:22,617 --> 00:12:25,404
She made two phone calls from the hotel,

182
00:12:25,495 --> 00:12:28,658
one to her parents and one to the Memphis School Board.

183
00:12:29,999 --> 00:12:33,162
She seemed a little reluctant.

184
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:35,995
I'd hate to lose this young man.

185
00:12:36,089 --> 00:12:37,750
I think she'll come around.

186
00:12:37,840 --> 00:12:40,582
What about Kozinski and Hodges?

187
00:12:41,302 --> 00:12:43,634
Have you spoken to Chicago?

188
00:12:44,639 --> 00:12:46,004
I have.

189
00:12:48,017 --> 00:12:49,473
It's not good.

190
00:12:50,687 --> 00:12:52,302
We're gonna have to do something.

191
00:13:06,869 --> 00:13:09,155
I drew the happy face.

192
00:13:10,665 --> 00:13:12,496
Where's Memphis?

193
00:13:47,994 --> 00:13:49,154
Is that it?

194
00:13:49,245 --> 00:13:51,577
- Yeah?
- It looks different.

195
00:13:51,664 --> 00:13:54,576
It's prettier than the pictures they sent.

196
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:40,793
"Mitch and Abby, we've taken the liberty
of furnishing the house temporarily.

197
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,711
"Just a few things to make you feel at home.

198
00:14:42,799 --> 00:14:44,460
"Hope you don't mind."

199
00:14:53,309 --> 00:14:54,594
Abby!

200
00:15:02,110 --> 00:15:03,816
Not bad, huh?

201
00:15:04,821 --> 00:15:06,152
Where's yours?

202
00:15:23,172 --> 00:15:25,504
- Don't get up.
- Don't worry.

203
00:15:38,020 --> 00:15:39,601
Mitchell McDeere.

204
00:15:39,689 --> 00:15:41,304
Tad eager are we, Mr. McDeere?

205
00:16:30,031 --> 00:16:31,316
What are you doing?

206
00:16:31,407 --> 00:16:33,068
Dutch says you've been here since 6:30.

207
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:34,649
I thought I'd jump start the bar exam work.

208
00:16:34,744 --> 00:16:37,076
Good. No associate has ever
failed the bar exam, you know.

209
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:38,903
Come on. I'll show you your new office.

210
00:16:39,040 --> 00:16:40,826
Wally Hudson, Contracts.

211
00:16:40,917 --> 00:16:42,578
- Here to help with the bar exam.
- Thanks, Wally.

212
00:16:42,710 --> 00:16:45,577
No associate of the Firm has ever failed the bar exam.

213
00:16:45,713 --> 00:16:47,999
The first day is a four-hour
multiple choice on ethics.

214
00:16:48,090 --> 00:16:52,584
Look at the first six chapters.
I'll see you Wednesday, 8:45.

215
00:16:52,678 --> 00:16:57,172
Oh, no associate of this firm
has ever failed the bar exam.

216
00:16:57,266 --> 00:16:58,927
No kidding.

217
00:16:59,018 --> 00:17:02,931
- Ken Curry. Domestic Relations.
- Mike Allen. Wills and Estates.

218
00:17:03,064 --> 00:17:04,600
Nina.

219
00:17:04,732 --> 00:17:06,347
Fuck! Please.

220
00:17:09,111 --> 00:17:10,726
I'm sorry. Can I help you?

221
00:17:10,821 --> 00:17:12,607
Actually, I think I'm here to help you.

222
00:17:12,698 --> 00:17:15,405
I'm Avery Tolar, your designated mentor.

223
00:17:15,493 --> 00:17:16,653
Let's go to lunch.

224
00:17:16,786 --> 00:17:18,276
Lunch? But it's not even...

225
00:17:18,371 --> 00:17:21,534
Not even noon, I know. It will be a working lunch.

226
00:17:21,624 --> 00:17:24,787
Come on up to my office while I drop this off.

227
00:17:26,796 --> 00:17:28,002
Everything depends on billing.

228
00:17:28,130 --> 00:17:30,166
How many hours you spend even thinking about a client.

229
00:17:30,299 --> 00:17:34,258
I don't care if you're stuck in traffic
or shaving or sitting on a park bench.

230
00:17:34,345 --> 00:17:35,801
Now, my particular field...

231
00:17:35,888 --> 00:17:38,129
Is forming limited partnerships
for offshore corporations,

232
00:17:38,224 --> 00:17:39,839
mainly in the Cayman Islands.

233
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:44,094
Good. I want you to review the last o
e I did for a client named Sonny Capps.

234
00:17:44,188 --> 00:17:45,803
He made over 14 million last year,

235
00:17:45,898 --> 00:17:48,435
paid less than 4% in taxes
and resents every buck of it.

236
00:17:48,526 --> 00:17:52,269
But he paid us $400,000 in fees,
so I don't want to make him unhappy.

237
00:17:52,363 --> 00:17:54,319
Take a look at the deal, see if
you can come up with anything.

238
00:17:54,407 --> 00:17:56,147
Madge, tell him I'll call him in the morning, please.

239
00:17:56,242 --> 00:17:58,153
Yes, Mr. Tolar. Should I save these for later?

240
00:17:58,244 --> 00:18:00,360
- Could you, please?
- What do you mean by "anything"?

241
00:18:00,496 --> 00:18:01,531
What do you think I mean?

242
00:18:01,664 --> 00:18:03,655
I don't know, you're the risk taker.

243
00:18:03,749 --> 00:18:05,580
Do you think I'm talking about breaking the law?

244
00:18:05,668 --> 00:18:08,250
No, I'm just trying to figure
out how far you want it bent.

245
00:18:08,337 --> 00:18:10,874
As far as you can without breaking it.

246
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:12,372
In other words, don't risk an IRS audit.

247
00:18:12,508 --> 00:18:15,215
I don't give a damn about an
audit. They just better not win.

248
00:18:16,345 --> 00:18:17,585
Yes, Mr. Tolar?

249
00:18:17,680 --> 00:18:19,545
Something before lunch?

250
00:18:19,682 --> 00:18:23,721
I should warn you the Firm frowns
on drinking during office hours.

251
00:18:23,853 --> 00:18:25,343
Iced tea, please.

252
00:18:25,438 --> 00:18:27,724
